04335nam a22005175i 9780773565753DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19961996xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735657537 a10.1515/97807735657532doi  a(DE-B1597)657692  a(OCoLC)1394872078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBX8251 ǂb S45 1996eb 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a287/.09711 aSemple, Neil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLord's Dominion :bThe History of Canadian Methodism /cNeil Semple. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (544 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Religion ;v2100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Origins of Methodism -- tThe Early Mission to British North America -- tMethodism as a Personal Spiritual and Moral Movement -- tUpper Canadian Wesleyan and Episcopal Methodism, 1820–54 -- tDivergent Visions: The Wesleyans in the Atlantic Region and the Smaller Connexions before 1855 -- tMass Evangelism before 1860 -- tThe Methodists and Native Peoples before 1860 -- tThe Elaboration of a National Methodist Church -- tThe Transformation of the Social Means of Grace -- tMethodist Education -- tMethodist Missions in Canada, 1854–1925 -- tMethodist Overseas Missions, 1873–1925 -- tMethodism and the Creation of a Moral Order -- tYoung People and the Methodist Moral Order -- tMethodism in the Early Twentieth Century -- tMethodism and the Formation of The United Church of Canada -- tMethodism–the Continuing Legacy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSemple covers virtually every aspect of Canadian Methodism. He examines early nineteenth-century efforts to evangelize pioneer British North America and the revivalistic activities so important to the mid-nineteenth-century years. He documents Methodists' missionary work both overseas and in Canada among aboriginal peoples and immigrants. He analyses the Methodist contribution to Canadian education and the leadership the church provided for the expansion of the role of women in society. He also assesses the spiritual and social dimensions of evangelical religion in the personal lives of Methodists, addressing such social issues as prohibition, prostitution, the importance of the family, and changing attitudes toward children in Methodist doctrine and Canada in general. Semple argues that Methodism evolved into the most Canadian of all the churches, helping to break down the geographic, political, economic, ethnic, and social divisions that confounded national unity. Although the Methodist Church did not achieve the universality it aspired to, he concludes that it succeeded in defining the religious, political, and social agenda for the Protestant component of Canada, providing a powerful legacy of service to humanity and to God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356575340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565753/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles